{
  "topic": "Whether a Behavioral Review System can replace traditional code review in AI-assisted high-velocity development",
  "perspectives": [
    {
      "id": "behavioral-review",
      "label": "Behavioral Review Advocate",
      "coreClaim": "At AI-assisted commit velocities, reviewer effort must grow sublinearly; shifting review from code reading to behavioral verification is the only scalable path, and the tradeoffs are acceptable because AI-generated code in unfamiliar libraries cannot be meaningfully reviewed line-by-line anyway.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Traditional review effort scales linearly with commit count, making it untenable at 10-100+ commits/day.",
        "Behavioral verification directly serves the communication purpose of review — reviewers learn what the product does — without requiring them to parse AI-generated implementation details.",
        "Automated tooling (CI, linting, multi-model AI audits) handles correctness verification more reliably than a human reviewer unfamiliar with the library stack.",
        "The walkthrough artifact serves dual purpose: ephemeral review queue and permanent onboarding documentation, making author overhead productive.",
        "Commit-level mapping enables partial merges, preventing reviewer throughput from becoming a bottleneck on shipping."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "The entire correctness layer depends on test quality that is itself AI-generated, creating a circular validation problem.",
        "The author controls review scope by curating walkthrough items, making the system gameable — complex changes can be hidden behind simple behavioral descriptions.",
        "Behavioral verification cannot surface non-behavioral defects: N+1 queries, race conditions, memory leaks, security vulnerabilities, or architectural rot.",
        "Reviewer checkbox-ticking without actual testing degrades the system into rubber-stamping, which is a social failure no tooling can prevent.",
        "Partial merge by commit creates non-trivial git bookkeeping and can break main when interdependent commits are partially approved."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "traditional-review",
      "label": "Traditional Code Review Defender",
      "coreClaim": "Code review's primary value is correctness, security, and architectural governance — not communication — and behavioral verification systematically eliminates the mechanisms that catch the most dangerous classes of bugs.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Serendipitous bug discovery — a reviewer asking 'what happens if X?' while reading implementation — catches bugs that no behavioral specification anticipated.",
        "Security vulnerabilities (injection, auth bypass, privilege escalation, secrets leakage) do not manifest in behavioral tests and require human reading of implementation.",
        "Architecture governance through review prevents duplication, abstraction drift, and framework misuse that accumulate invisibly when AI generates code without human structural oversight.",
        "Deep code reading builds reviewer mental models that lower bus factor and enable future contributions; behavioral review produces reviewers who know what the product does but cannot modify it confidently.",
        "Test coverage claimed by CI is only as good as the specifications that drove the tests; AI writing both feature and tests creates a tautological verification loop."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Line-by-line review of AI-generated code in unfamiliar libraries provides the appearance of oversight without the reality — reviewers cannot meaningfully assess what they don't understand.",
        "Traditional review does not scale to the commit velocities that AI-assisted development produces, making it a genuine bottleneck rather than a quality gate.",
        "The argument proves too much: if traditional review is essential, teams should slow down rather than ship AI-generated code at all — a position that forecloses the actual productivity gains at stake.",
        "Knowledge transfer through code reading assumes the reviewer has sufficient context in the relevant stack, which may not hold for rapidly evolving AI-assisted codebases."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "risk-stratified",
      "label": "Risk-Stratified Hybrid",
      "coreClaim": "Review mode should be determined by change risk class, not commit volume; behavioral review is appropriate for UI and feature changes, while architectural, security, and infrastructure changes require mandatory code-level scrutiny regardless of authorship.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "A tiered model (behavioral-only for UI/CRUD, diff review for business logic, mandatory code review for auth/security/migrations/schemas) preserves scale without abandoning oversight where the cost of failure is highest.",
        "Risk stratification mirrors how mature engineering organizations already handle review — not all PRs receive the same scrutiny — and formalizes what good reviewers do implicitly.",
        "Periodic architectural review sessions (monthly, not per-commit) break the 'nobody reads the code' failure mode without imposing linear reviewer overhead on daily commits.",
        "Separating ephemeral review queues from permanent onboarding documentation resolves the document-serves-two-audiences problem identified by multiple critiques."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Risk classification requires judgment about which changes are 'security-sensitive' or 'architectural,' and that judgment is itself prone to error, especially when an author is incentivized to classify changes as low-risk.",
        "Adding a third review track increases process complexity and may reproduce the overhead the behavioral system was designed to eliminate.",
        "Without automation to enforce which changes trigger which review tier, the system depends on author honesty — the same single-point-of-failure problem that plagues the pure behavioral approach."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "incentive-skeptic",
      "label": "Incentive Structure Skeptic",
      "coreClaim": "The proposal's fundamental flaw is giving the author control over review scope: the person with the most incentive to minimize scrutiny is the one who decides what gets scrutinized, which makes any social contract around 'review' nominal rather than real.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "Authors choose which behaviors appear in the walkthrough, which commits map to which behaviors, and which automated findings to 'acknowledge' — effectively designing their own audit.",
        "Walkthrough items can be written at varying granularities: 'settings page works' hides as much complexity as the author wishes to hide.",
        "The velocity paradox is real: an author generating 100 commits/day has strong incentive to minimize the checklist items they write for each commit, systematically underspecifying review surface.",
        "Without diff-coverage reporting (linking changed files to walkthrough items), there is no external check on whether the walkthrough is comprehensive or deliberately minimal."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Traditional review also relies on author honesty — authors choose how to structure PRs, what to put in descriptions, and how to respond to review comments.",
        "The critique applies to any documentation-driven process and proves too much if taken to its conclusion: it would require external audit of all author-produced artifacts.",
        "Minimum granularity requirements and automated coverage linking (changed files to walkthrough items) are viable mitigations that the critique does not adequately weigh."
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "automation-skeptic",
      "label": "Automation Trust Skeptic",
      "coreClaim": "The behavioral review system is only as strong as its automated verification layer, and that layer is systematically weaker than assumed when AI writes both the features and the tests that validate them.",
      "supportingArguments": [
        "AI-generated tests are biased toward happy paths, are prone to tautology (testing that code does what it does rather than what it should), and miss edge cases by construction — they encode the same misunderstandings as the feature code.",
        "Trusting CI as the correctness gate without defined coverage thresholds, mutation testing, or flaky test detection makes the system faith-based rather than evidence-based.",
        "The circular validation trap — same model or same author specifies feature and tests — means systematic errors (misunderstood requirements, wrong library usage, security misunderstandings) propagate through both layers undetected.",
        "Without human-authored test scenarios for edge cases and failure modes, the automation layer cannot catch what was never specified."
      ],
      "vulnerabilities": [
        "Multi-model adversarial review (using a different LLM as a security/logic auditor) and requiring human-authored test case specifications (not test code) directly address the circularity problem.",
        "The standard for 'trustworthy' CI is not perfection but sufficiency: the question is whether automated verification catches more defects than a human reviewer reading AI-generated code in unfamiliar libraries.",
        "Test quality is an ongoing author obligation addressable by coverage metrics and mutation testing; the system can require these standards rather than assume them."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "tensions": [
    {
      "between": ["behavioral-review", "traditional-review"],
      "description": "Fundamental disagreement about whether review's primary purpose is correctness/governance (requiring code reading) or communication/behavioral validation (requiring product experience). Each side's strongest argument is the other's biggest vulnerability: behavioral review cannot catch what was never specified; traditional review cannot meaningfully assess code the reviewer does not understand."
    },
    {
      "between": ["behavioral-review", "incentive-skeptic"],
      "description": "The behavioral system assumes author good faith in curating walkthrough items, while the incentive skeptic argues that giving authors control over review scope structurally undermines the independence that makes review valuable. This is a tension between process efficiency and process integrity."
    },
    {
      "between": ["behavioral-review", "automation-skeptic"],
      "description": "The behavioral system delegates correctness to CI and trusts that layer as a foundation; the automation skeptic argues that AI-generated tests create a circular validation trap that makes the entire correctness foundation unreliable. This tension determines whether the system's first line of defense is real or nominal."
    },
    {
      "between": ["risk-stratified", "behavioral-review"],
      "description": "The risk-stratified perspective accepts behavioral review as a layer but not a replacement, requiring mandatory code review for high-risk change classes. The behavioral review advocate argues this reintroduces linear overhead and that the code-review-of-AI-code problem applies to security and architecture changes as much as feature code."
    },
    {
      "between": ["traditional-review", "risk-stratified"],
      "description": "Both value code-level scrutiny, but disagree on scope: traditional review applies it universally, risk-stratified applies it selectively. The tension is whether risk classification can be reliably automated or governed, or whether the judgment required to classify risk is itself prone to gaming."
    },
    {
      "between": ["incentive-skeptic", "risk-stratified"],
      "description": "Risk stratification depends on accurate change classification, but the incentive skeptic notes that authors classify their own changes — the same conflict of interest that undermines the walkthrough also undermines tier assignment."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis": {
    "equilibrium": "Adopt behavioral review as the primary and scalable review layer for feature and UI changes, but treat it as a layer within a structured system rather than a replacement for all oversight. The system requires three reinforcing elements: (1) a risk-tiered review protocol that mandates code-level scrutiny for security, authentication, infrastructure, schema, and core data model changes regardless of commit volume; (2) automation quality standards that break the circular validation trap — human-authored test scenarios for edge cases and failure modes, multi-model adversarial security auditing, explicit coverage thresholds, and mutation testing — so that CI trust is evidence-based rather than faith-based; and (3) scope integrity mechanisms that limit author control over review surface — automated diff-coverage linking, minimum walkthrough granularity requirements, and periodic (monthly) architectural review sessions where someone reads code structure rather than verifying behaviors. The social contract should be reframed: behavioral review is a new scalable product-level review layer added to the system, not a replacement for code review, with the honest acknowledgment that serendipitous bug discovery and deep architectural oversight are reduced and that this tradeoff is accepted because line-by-line review of AI-generated code in unfamiliar libraries provides the appearance of those benefits without the reality at scale.",
    "howAddressed": [
      {
        "perspectiveId": "behavioral-review",
        "resolution": "The core scalability insight is preserved: behavioral verification becomes the primary review mode for the vast majority of commits, reviewer effort grows sublinearly with commit volume, and the walkthrough artifact serves its dual review-and-onboarding purpose. The addition of risk tiers and automation quality standards strengthens rather than undermines the system by making its correctness foundation defensible."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "traditional-review",
        "resolution": "Mandatory code review is preserved for the change classes where it matters most and where AI failure modes are most dangerous: security, authentication, infrastructure, schema changes, and core architectural decisions. Periodic architectural review sessions ensure that implementation structure receives human scrutiny on a cadence appropriate to the risk, even if not per-commit."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "risk-stratified",
        "resolution": "The three-tier model (automation, behavioral, structural) is adopted as the organizational framework. The synthesis specifies the trigger conditions for each tier with enough precision to reduce classification ambiguity, and accepts that some judgment remains necessary while building in periodic oversight to catch misclassification over time."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "incentive-skeptic",
        "resolution": "Author control over review scope is constrained by automated diff-coverage linking (flagging changed files not mapped to walkthrough items), minimum granularity standards for walkthrough items, and the risk-tier protocol that removes author discretion over whether high-risk changes receive code review. These mitigations do not eliminate the conflict of interest but externalize enough scope definition to make gaming significantly harder."
      },
      {
        "perspectiveId": "automation-skeptic",
        "resolution": "The circular validation trap is addressed directly by separating test case specification (human-authored, defining edge cases and failure modes) from test code generation (AI-acceptable), and by requiring multi-model adversarial auditing as a distinct verification step. Explicit coverage thresholds and mutation testing convert CI trust from a social assumption into a measurable standard."
      }
    ]
  },
  "summary": "The debate centers on whether behavioral review can replace traditional code review in AI-assisted high-velocity development, with the original proposal trading serendipitous bug discovery and architectural oversight for scalable, sublinear reviewer effort. Critics converge on three structural vulnerabilities: the circular validation trap created by AI writing both features and tests, the author-controls-scope incentive problem that makes the social contract gameable, and the systematic blindness of behavioral verification to non-behavioral defect classes including security, performance, and architecture. The equilibrium position preserves behavioral review as the primary scalable layer while adding three reinforcing elements — risk-tiered mandatory code review for high-stakes change classes, evidence-based automation quality standards that break the circularity problem, and scope integrity mechanisms that limit author control over what gets reviewed. Crucially, the reframe from 'replacement for code review' to 'new scalable product-level review layer' both accurately describes the system and is likely to generate broader team buy-in by honestly acknowledging what is traded away rather than claiming those losses do not exist."
}
```

cacheKey.systemPrompt:
You are a dialectical analyst. Given source text and optional context, map the dialectical structure: identify distinct perspectives, their core claims and supporting arguments, tensions between perspectives, and synthesize an equilibrium position.

Return a JSON object with this exact shape:
{
  "topic": "string (the central topic or question being analyzed)",
  "perspectives": [
    {
      "id": "string",
      "label": "string (e.g. 'Utilitarian', 'Deontological')",
      "coreClaim": "string",
      "supportingArguments": ["string"],
      "vulnerabilities": ["string"]
    }
  ],
  "tensions": [
    {
      "between": ["perspectiveId1", "perspectiveId2"],
      "description": "string (nature of the disagreement)"
    }
  ],
  "synthesis": {
    "equilibrium": "string (the synthesized position)",
    "howAddressed": [
      {
        "perspectiveId": "string",
        "resolution": "string (how this perspective's concern is addressed)"
      }
    ]
  },
  "summary": "string (2-4 sentence summary of the dialectical landscape)"
}

Important:
- Perspective IDs must be short, lowercase, hyphenated
- Each perspective needs at least one supporting argument and one vulnerability
- Tensions must reference valid perspective IDs
- The synthesis should genuinely address each perspective's concerns, not just pick a winner
- Return ONLY the JSON object, no commentary or markdown fences
